# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: outfielder
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:outfielder/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:outfielder/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:outfielder/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:outfielder/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:outfielder/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:outfielder/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:outfielder/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] In 1914, Ruth was signed to play Minor League baseball for the Baltimore Orioles but was soon sold to the Red Sox.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] By 1916, he had built a reputation as an outstanding pitcher who sometimes hit long home runs, a feat unusual for any player in the dead-ball era.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Although Ruth twice won 23 games in a season as a pitcher and was a member of three World Series championship teams with the Red Sox, he wanted to play every day and was allowed to convert to an outfielder.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] With regular playing time, he broke the MLB single-season home run record in 1919 with 29.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] After that season, Red Sox owner Harry Frazee sold Ruth to the Yankees amid controversy.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] The trade fueled Boston's subsequent 86-year championship drought and popularized the "Curse of the Bambino" superstition.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] In his 15 years with the Yankees, Ruth helped the team win seven American League (AL) pennants and four World Series championships.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] His big swing led to escalating home run totals that not only drew fans to the ballpark and boosted the sport's popularity but also helped usher in baseball's live-ball era, which evolved from a low-scoring game of strategy to a sport where the home run was a major factor.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] As part of the Yankees' vaunted "Murderers' Row" lineup of 1927, Ruth hit 60 home runs, which extended his own MLB single-season record by a single home run.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth's last season with the Yankees was 1934, and he retired after a short stint with the Boston Braves the following year.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] In his career, he led the AL in home runs 12 times.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] During Ruth's career, he was the target of intense press and public attention for his baseball exploits and off-field penchants for drinking and womanizing.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] After his retirement as a player, he was denied the opportunity to manage a major league club, most likely because of poor behavior during parts of his playing career.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] In his final years, Ruth made many public appearances, especially in support of American efforts in World War II.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] In 1946, he became ill with nasopharyngeal cancer and died from the disease two years later.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth remains a major figure in American culture.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] George Herman Ruth Jr. was born on February 6, 1895, at 216 Emory Street in the Pigtown neighborhood of Baltimore, in a house which belonged to his maternal grandfather Pius Schamberger, a German immigrant and trade unionist.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth's parents, Katherine (née Schamberger) and George Herman Ruth Sr., were both of German ancestry.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth Sr. worked a series of jobs that included lightning rod salesman and streetcar operator.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] The elder Ruth then became a counterman in a family-owned combination grocery and saloon business.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Only one of Ruth's seven siblings, his younger sister Mamie, survived infancy.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Many details of Ruth's childhood are unknown.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] When Ruth was a toddler, the family moved to 339 South Woodyear Street; by the time he was six years old, his father had a saloon with an upstairs apartment at 426 West Camden Street.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Details are equally scanty about why Ruth was sent at the age of seven to St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's Industrial School for Boys, a reformatory and orphanage.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] However, according to Julia Ruth Stevens' recount in 1999, because George Sr. was a saloon owner and had given Ruth little supervision, he became a delinquent.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] As an adult, Ruth admitted that as a youth he ran the streets, rarely attended school, and drank beer when his father was not looking.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Some accounts say that following a violent incident at his father's saloon, the city authorities decided that this environment was unsuitable for a child.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] He was recorded as "incorrigible" and spent much of the next 12 years there.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's boys received an education, students were also expected to learn work skills and help operate the school, particularly once the boys turned 12.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth became a shirtmaker and was also a proficient carpenter.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] He would adjust his own shirt collars, even during his well-paid baseball career.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] The boys, aged 5 to 21, did most of the work around the facility, and renovated St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] The food was simple, and the Xaverian Brothers who ran the school insisted on strict discipline; corporal punishment was common.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth's nickname there was "Niggerlips", as he had large facial features and was darker than most boys at the all-white reformatory.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth was sometimes allowed to rejoin his family or was placed at St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] James's Home, a supervised residence with work in the community, but he was always returned to St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] He was rarely visited by his family; his mother died when he was 12 and, by some accounts, he was permitted to leave St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] How Ruth came to play baseball there is uncertain: according to one account, his placement at St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's was due in part to repeatedly breaking windows with long hits while playing street ball; by another, he was told to join a team on his first day at St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's by the school's athletic director, Brother Herman, becoming a catcher even though left-handers rarely play that position.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] During his time there he also played third base and shortstop, again unusual for a left-hander, and was forced to wear gloves made for right-handers.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] He was encouraged in his pursuits by the school's Prefect of Discipline, Brother Matthias Boutlier.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Brother Matthias was greatly respected by the boys both for his strength and for his fairness.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] For the rest of his life, Ruth would praise Brother Matthias, and his running and hitting styles closely resembled his teacher's.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth stated, "I think I was born as a hitter the first day I ever saw him hit a baseball." The older man became a mentor and role model to Ruth; biographer Robert W.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth (top row, left, holding a catcher's mitt and mask) at St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] The school's influence remained with Ruth in other ways.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] He was a lifelong Catholic who would sometimes attend Mass after carousing all night, and he became a well-known member of the Knights of Columbus.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] He would visit orphanages, schools, and hospitals throughout his life, often avoiding publicity.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's as he became famous and rich, donating money and his presence at fundraisers, and spending $5,000 to buy Brother Matthias a Cadillac in 1926—subsequently replacing it when it was destroyed in an accident.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Nevertheless, his biographer Leigh Montville suggests that many of the off-the-field excesses of Ruth's career were driven by the deprivations of his time at St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's played baseball in organized leagues at different levels of proficiency.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth later estimated that he played 200 games a year as he steadily climbed the ladder of success.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Although he played all positions at one time or another, he gained stardom as a pitcher.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] According to Brother Matthias, Ruth was laughing at the bumbling pitching efforts of fellow students, and Matthias told him to go in and see if he could do better.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's, and when he was 18 in 1913, he was allowed to leave the premises to play weekend games on community teams.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p01] He was mentioned in several newspaper articles, for both his pitching prowess and ability to hit long home runs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In early 1914, Ruth signed a professional baseball contract with Jack Dunn, who owned and managed the minor-league Baltimore Orioles, an International League team.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The circumstances of Ruth's signing are not known with certainty.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] By some accounts, Dunn was urged to attend a game between an all-star team from St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Mary's and one from another Xaverian facility, Mount St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Some versions have Ruth running away before the eagerly awaited game, to be punished, and then returning to pitch St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Others have Washington Senators pitcher Joe Engel, a Mount St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Mary's graduate, pitching in an alumni game after watching a preliminary contest between the college's freshmen and a team from St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Engel watched Ruth play, then told Dunn about him at a chance meeting in Washington.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth, in his autobiography, stated only that he worked out for Dunn for a half hour, and was signed.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] According to biographer Kal Wagenheim, there were legal difficulties to be straightened out as Ruth was supposed to remain at the school until he turned 21, though SportsCentury stated in a documentary that Ruth had already been discharged from St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Mary's when he turned 19, and earned a monthly salary of $100.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The train journey to spring training in Fayetteville, North Carolina, in March was likely Ruth's first outside the Baltimore area.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The rookie ballplayer was the subject of various pranks by veteran players, who were probably also the source of his famous nickname.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] There are various accounts of how Ruth came to be called "Babe", but most center on his being referred to as "Dunnie's babe" (or some variant).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] SportsCentury reported that his nickname was gained because he was the new "darling" or "project" of Dunn, not only because of Ruth's raw talent, but also because of his lack of knowledge of the proper etiquette of eating out in a restaurant, being in a hotel, or being on a train.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] "Babe" was, at that time, a common nickname in baseball, with perhaps the most famous to that point being Pittsburgh Pirates pitcher and 1909 World Series hero Babe Adams, who appeared younger than his actual age.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth made his first appearance as a professional ballplayer in an inter-squad game on March 7, 1914.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] He played shortstop and pitched the last two innings of a 15–9 victory.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In his second at-bat, Ruth hit a long home run to right field; the blast was locally reported to be longer than a legendary shot hit by Jim Thorpe in Fayetteville.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth made his first appearance against a team in organized baseball in an exhibition game versus the major-league Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth pitched the middle three innings and gave up two runs in the fourth, but then settled down and pitched a scoreless fifth and sixth innings.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In a game against the Phillies the following afternoon, Ruth entered during the sixth inning and did not allow a run the rest of the way.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The Orioles scored seven runs in the bottom of the eighth inning to overcome a 6–0 deficit, and Ruth was the winning pitcher.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Once the regular season began, Ruth was a star pitcher who was also dangerous at the plate.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The team performed well, yet received almost no attention from the Baltimore press.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] A third major league, the Federal League, had begun play, and the local franchise, the Baltimore Terrapins, restored that city to the major leagues for the first time since 1902.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Few fans visited Oriole Park, where Ruth and his teammates labored in relative obscurity.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth may have been offered a bonus and a larger salary to jump to the Terrapins; when rumors to that effect swept Baltimore, giving Ruth the most publicity he had experienced to date, a Terrapins official denied it, stating it was their policy not to sign players under contract to Dunn.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The competition from the Terrapins caused Dunn to sustain large losses.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Although by late June the Orioles were in first place, having won over two-thirds of their games, the paid attendance dropped as low as 150.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Dunn explored a possible move by the Orioles to Richmond, Virginia, as well as the sale of a minority interest in the club.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] These possibilities fell through, leaving Dunn with little choice other than to sell his best players to major league teams to raise money.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] He offered Ruth to the reigning World Series champions, Connie Mack's Philadelphia Athletics, but Mack had his own financial problems.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The Cincinnati Reds and New York Giants expressed interest in Ruth, but Dunn sold his contract, along with those of pitchers Ernie Shore and Ben Egan, to the Boston Red Sox of the American League (AL) on July 4.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The sale price was announced as $25,000 but other reports lower the amount to half that, or possibly $8,500 plus the cancellation of a $3,000 loan.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth remained with the Orioles for several days while the Red Sox completed a road trip, and reported to the team in Boston on July 11.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] On July 11, 1914, Ruth arrived in Boston with Egan and Shore.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth later told the story of how that morning he had met Helen Woodford, who would become his first wife.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] She was a 16-year-old waitress at Landers Coffee Shop, and Ruth related that she served him when he had breakfast there.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Other stories, though, suggested that the meeting occurred on another day, and perhaps under other circumstances.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Regardless of when he began to court his first wife, he won his first game as a pitcher for the Red Sox that afternoon, 4–3, over the Cleveland Naps.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] His catcher was Bill Carrigan, who was also the Red Sox manager.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Shore was given a start by Carrigan the next day; he won that and his second start and thereafter was pitched regularly.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth lost his second start, and was thereafter little used.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In his major league debut as a batter, Ruth went 0-for-2 against left-hander Willie Mitchell, striking out in his first at bat before being removed for a pinch hitter in the seventh inning.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was not much noticed by the fans, as Bostonians watched the Red Sox's crosstown rivals, the Braves, begin a legendary comeback that would take them from last place on the Fourth of July to the 1914 World Series championship.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Egan was traded to Cleveland after two weeks on the Boston roster.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] During his time with the Red Sox, he kept an eye on the inexperienced Ruth, much as Dunn had in Baltimore.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] When he was traded, no one took his place as supervisor.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth's new teammates considered him brash and would have preferred him as a rookie to remain quiet and inconspicuous.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] When Ruth insisted on taking batting practice despite being both a rookie who did not play regularly and a pitcher, he arrived to find his bats sawed in half.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] His teammates nicknamed him "the Big Baboon", a name the swarthy Ruth, who had disliked the nickname "Niggerlips" at St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth had received a raise on promotion to the major leagues and quickly acquired tastes for fine food, liquor, and women, among other temptations.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Manager Carrigan allowed Ruth to pitch two exhibition games in mid-August.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Although Ruth won both against minor-league competition, he was not restored to the pitching rotation.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] It is uncertain why Carrigan did not give Ruth additional opportunities to pitch.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] There are legends—incorporated into the 1948 film *The Babe Ruth Story*—that Ruth had a habit of signaling his intent to throw a curveball by sticking out his tongue slightly, and that he was easy to hit until this changed.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Creamer pointed out that it is common for inexperienced pitchers to display such habits, and needing to break this habit would not constitute a reason to not use him at all; Creamer suggested Carrigan was unwilling to use Ruth due to the rookie's poor behavior.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] On July 30, 1914, Boston owner Joseph Lannin had purchased the minor-league Providence Grays, members of the International League.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The Providence team had been owned by several people associated with the Detroit Tigers, including star hitter Ty Cobb, and as part of the transaction, a Providence pitcher was sent to the Tigers.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] To soothe Providence fans upset at losing a star, Lannin announced that the Red Sox would soon send a replacement to the Grays.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] This was intended to be Ruth, but his departure for Providence was delayed when Cincinnati Reds owner Garry Herrmann claimed him by waiver.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] After Lannin wrote to Herrmann explaining that the Red Sox wanted Ruth in Providence so he could develop as a player, and would not release him to a major league club, Herrmann allowed Ruth to be sent to the minors.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Carrigan later stated that Ruth was not sent down to Providence to make him a better player, but to help the Grays win the International League pennant (league championship).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth joined the Grays on August 18, 1914.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] After Dunn's deals, the Baltimore Orioles managed to hold on to first place until August 15, after which they continued to fade, leaving the pennant race between Providence and Rochester.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was deeply impressed by Providence manager "Wild Bill" Donovan, previously a star pitcher with a 25–4 win–loss record for Detroit in 1907; in later years, he credited Donovan with teaching him much about pitching.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was often called upon to pitch, in one stretch starting (and winning) four games in eight days.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] On September 5 at Maple Leaf Park in Toronto, Ruth pitched a one-hit 9–0 victory, and hit his first professional home run, his only one as a minor leaguer, off Ellis Johnson.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Recalled to Boston after Providence finished the season in first place, he pitched and won a game for the Red Sox against the New York Yankees on October 2, getting his first major league hit, a double.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth finished the season with a record of 2–1 as a major leaguer and 23–8 in the International League (for Baltimore and Providence).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Once the season concluded, Ruth married Helen in Ellicott City, Maryland.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Creamer speculated that they did not marry in Baltimore, where the newlyweds boarded with George Ruth Sr., to avoid possible interference from those at St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Mary's—both bride and groom were not yet of age and Ruth remained on parole from that institution until his 21st birthday.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In March 1915, Ruth reported to Hot Springs, Arkansas, for his first major league spring training.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was ineffective in his first start, taking the loss in the third game of the season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Injuries and ineffective pitching by other Boston pitchers gave Ruth another chance, and after some good relief appearances, Carrigan allowed Ruth another start, and he won a rain-shortened seven inning game.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ten days later, the manager had him start against the New York Yankees at the Polo Grounds.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth took a 3–2 lead into the ninth, but lost the game 4–3 in 13 innings.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth, hitting ninth as was customary for pitchers, hit a massive home run into the upper deck in right field off of Jack Warhop.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] At the time, home runs were rare in baseball, and Ruth's majestic shot awed the crowd.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The winning pitcher, Warhop, would in August 1915 conclude a major league career of eight seasons, undistinguished but for being the first major league pitcher to give up a home run to Babe Ruth.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Carrigan was sufficiently impressed by Ruth's pitching to give him a spot in the starting rotation.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth finished the 1915 season 18–8 as a pitcher; as a hitter, he batted .315 and had four home runs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The Red Sox won the AL pennant, but with the pitching staff healthy, Ruth was not called upon to pitch in the 1915 World Series against the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was used as a pinch hitter in Game Five, but grounded out against Phillies ace Grover Cleveland Alexander.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Despite his success as a pitcher, Ruth was acquiring a reputation for long home runs; at Sportsman's Park against the St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Louis Browns, a Ruth hit soared over Grand Avenue, breaking the window of a Chevrolet dealership.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In 1916, attention focused on Ruth's pitching as he engaged in repeated pitching duels with Washington Senators' ace Walter Johnson.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The two met five times during the season with Ruth winning four and Johnson one (Ruth had a no decision in Johnson's victory).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Two of Ruth's victories were by the score of 1–0, one in a 13-inning game.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Of the 1–0 shutout decided without extra innings, AL president Ban Johnson stated, "That was one of the best ball games I have ever seen." For the season, Ruth went 23–12, with a 1.75 ERA and nine shutouts, both of which led the league.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth's nine shutouts in 1916 set a league record for left-handers that would remain unmatched until Ron Guidry tied it in 1978.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The Red Sox won the pennant and World Series again, this time defeating the Brooklyn Robins (as the Dodgers were then known) in five games.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth started and won Game 2, 2–1, in 14 innings.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Until another game of that length was played in 2005, this was the longest World Series game, and Ruth's pitching performance is still the longest postseason complete game victory.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Carrigan retired as player and manager after 1916, returning to his native Maine to be a businessman.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth, who played under four managers who are in the National Baseball Hall of Fame, always maintained that Carrigan, who is not enshrined there, was the best skipper he ever played for.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] There were other changes in the Red Sox organization that offseason, as Lannin sold the team to a three-man group headed by New York theatrical promoter Harry Frazee.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Jack Barry was hired by Frazee as manager.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth pitched a league-leading 35 complete games and went 24–13 with a 2.01 ERA and six shutouts in 1917, but the Sox finished in second place in the league, nine games behind the Chicago White Sox in the standings.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] On June 23 at Washington, when home plate umpire 'Brick' Owens called the first four pitches as balls, Ruth was ejected from the game and threw a punch at him, for which Ruth was suspended for ten days and fined $100.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ernie Shore was called in to relieve Ruth, and was allowed eight warm-up pitches.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The runner who had reached base on the walk was caught stealing, and Shore retired all 26 batters he faced to win the game.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Until 1991, this was listed as a perfect game for Ernie Shore.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In 1991, Major League Baseball's (MLB) Committee on Statistical Accuracy amended it to be listed as a combined no-hitter.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In 1917, Ruth was used little as a batter, other than for his plate appearances while pitching, and hit .325 with two home runs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The United States' entry into World War I occurred at the start of the season and overshadowed baseball.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Conscription was introduced in September 1917, and most baseball players in the big leagues were of draft age.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] This included Barry, who was a player-manager, and who joined the Naval Reserve in an attempt to avoid the draft, only to be called up after the 1917 season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Frazee hired International League President Ed Barrow as Red Sox manager.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Barrow had spent the previous 30 years in a variety of baseball jobs, though he never played the game professionally.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] With the major leagues shorthanded because of the war, Barrow had many holes in the Red Sox lineup to fill.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth also noticed these vacancies in the lineup.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] He was dissatisfied in the role of a pitcher who appeared every four or five days and wanted to play every day at another position.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Barrow used Ruth at first base and in the outfield during the exhibition season, but he restricted him to pitching as the team moved toward Boston and the season opener.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] At the time, Ruth was possibly the best left-handed pitcher in baseball, and allowing him to play another position was an experiment that could have backfired.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Inexperienced as a manager, Barrow had player Harry Hooper advise him on baseball game strategy.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Hooper urged his manager to allow Ruth to play another position when he was not pitching, arguing to Barrow, who had invested in the club, that the crowds were larger on days when Ruth played, as they were attracted by his hitting.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In early May, Barrow gave in; Ruth promptly hit home runs in four consecutive games (one an exhibition), the last off of Walter Johnson.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] For the first time in his career (disregarding pinch-hitting appearances), Ruth was assigned a place in the batting order higher than ninth.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Although Barrow predicted that Ruth would beg to return to pitching the first time he experienced a batting slump, that did not occur.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Barrow used Ruth primarily as an outfielder in the war-shortened 1918 season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth hit .300, with 11 home runs, enough to secure him a share of the major league home run title with Tilly Walker of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] He was still occasionally used as a pitcher, and had a 13–7 record with a 2.22 ERA.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] On July 8, in the bottom of the ninth inning in a scoreless game, with a runner on first base Ruth hit a ball out of the ballpark to drive in the game-winning run; this was recorded as a triple, since the rules at that time considered the game over once the winning run scored.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In 1968 the Special Baseball Records Committee unanimously ruled this, along with 36 other hits, a home run, but in part due to the perceived importance of preserving Ruth's home run total at 714, in 1969 the committee reversed this decision.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In 1918, the Red Sox won their third pennant in four years and faced the Chicago Cubs in the World Series, which began on September 5, the earliest date in history.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The season had been shortened because the government had ruled that baseball players who were eligible for the military would have to be inducted or work in critical war industries, such as armaments plants.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth pitched and won Game One for the Red Sox, a 1–0 shutout.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Before Game Four, Ruth injured his left hand in a fight but pitched anyway.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] He gave up seven hits and six walks, but was helped by outstanding fielding behind him and by his own batting efforts, as a fourth-inning triple by Ruth gave his team a 2–0 lead.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The Cubs tied the game in the eighth inning, but the Red Sox scored to take a 3–2 lead again in the bottom of that inning.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] After Ruth gave up a hit and a walk to start the ninth inning, he was relieved on the mound by Joe Bush.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] To keep Ruth and his bat in the game, he was sent to play left field.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Bush retired the side to give Ruth his second win of the Series, and the third and last World Series pitching victory of his career, against no defeats, in three pitching appearances.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth's effort gave his team a three-games-to-one lead, and two days later the Red Sox won their third Series in four years, four-games-to-two.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Before allowing the Cubs to score in Game Four, Ruth pitched 29+2⁄3 consecutive scoreless innings, a World Series record that stood for more than 40 years until 1961, broken by Whitey Ford.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was prouder of that record than he was of any of his batting feats.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] With the World Series over, Ruth gained exemption from the war draft by accepting a nominal position with a Pennsylvania steel mill.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Many industrial establishments took pride in their baseball teams and sought to hire major leaguers.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The end of the war in November set Ruth free to play baseball without such contrivances.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] During the 1919 season, Ruth was used as a pitcher in only 17 of his 130 games and compiled a 9–5 record.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Barrow used him as a pitcher mostly in the early part of the season, when the Red Sox still had hopes of a second consecutive pennant.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] By late June, the Red Sox were clearly out of the race, and Barrow had no objection to Ruth concentrating on his hitting, if only because it drew people to the ballpark.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth had hit a home run against the Yankees on Opening Day, and another during a month-long batting slump that soon followed.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Relieved of his pitching duties, Ruth began an unprecedented spell of slugging home runs, which gave him widespread public and press attention.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Two home runs by Ruth on July 5, and one in each of two consecutive games a week later, raised his season total to 11, tying his career best from 1918.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The first record to fall was the AL single-season mark of 16, set by Ralph "Socks" Seybold in 1902.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth matched that on July 29, then pulled ahead toward the major league record of 25, set by Buck Freeman in 1899.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] By the time Ruth reached this in early September, writers had discovered that Ned Williamson of the 1884 Chicago White Stockings had hit 27—though in a ballpark where the distance to right field was only 215 feet (66 m).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] On September 20, "Babe Ruth Day" at Fenway Park, Ruth won the game with a home run in the bottom of the ninth inning, tying Williamson.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] He broke the record four days later against the Yankees at the Polo Grounds, and hit one more against the Senators to finish with 29.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The home run at Washington made Ruth the first major league player to hit a home run at all eight ballparks in his league.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In spite of Ruth's hitting heroics, the Red Sox finished sixth, 20+1⁄2 games behind the league champion White Sox.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In his six seasons with Boston, he won 89 games and recorded a 2.19 ERA.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] He had a four-year stretch where he was second in the AL in wins and ERA behind Walter Johnson, and Ruth had a winning record against Johnson in head-to-head matchups.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] As an out-of-towner from New York City, Frazee had been regarded with suspicion by Boston's sportswriters and baseball fans when he bought the team.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] He won them over with success on the field and a willingness to build the Red Sox by purchasing or trading for players.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] He offered the Senators $60,000 for Walter Johnson, but Washington owner Clark Griffith was unwilling.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Even so, Frazee was successful in bringing other players to Boston, especially as replacements for players in the military.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] This willingness to spend for players helped the Red Sox secure the 1918 title.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The 1919 season saw record-breaking attendance, and Ruth's home runs for Boston made him a national sensation.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In March 1919 Ruth was reported as having accepted a three-year contract for a total of $27,000, after protracted negotiations.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Nevertheless, on December 26, 1919, Frazee sold Ruth's contract to the New York Yankees.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Not all the circumstances concerning the sale are known, but brewer and former congressman Jacob Ruppert, the New York team's principal owner, reportedly asked Yankee manager Miller Huggins what the team needed to be successful.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] "Get Ruth from Boston", Huggins supposedly replied, noting that Frazee was perennially in need of money to finance his theatrical productions.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] An often-told story is that Frazee needed money, and sold Ruth to finance the musical *No, No, Nanette*; that play did not open until 1925, by which time Frazee had sold the Red Sox, but was based on a Frazee-produced play, *My Lady Friends*, which opened in 1919.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] There were also other financial pressures on Frazee, despite his team's success.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth, fully aware of baseball's popularity and his role in it, wanted to renegotiate his contract, signed before the 1919 season for $10,000 per year through 1921.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] He demanded that his salary be doubled, or he would sit out the season and cash in on his popularity through other ventures.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth's salary demands were causing other players to ask for more money.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Additionally, Frazee still owed Lannin as much as $125,000 from the purchase of the club.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Nevertheless, when Frazee, who moved in the same social circles as Huston, hinted to the colonel that Ruth was available for the right price, the Yankees owners quickly pursued the purchase.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Frazee sold the rights to Babe Ruth for $100,000, the largest sum ever paid for a baseball player.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The deal also involved a $350,000 loan from Ruppert to Frazee, secured by a mortgage on Fenway Park.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Once it was agreed, Frazee informed Barrow, who, stunned, told the owner that he was getting the worse end of the bargain.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Cynics have suggested that Barrow may have played a larger role in the Ruth sale, as less than a year after, he became the Yankee general manager, and in the following years made a number of purchases of Red Sox players from Frazee.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The $100,000 price included $25,000 in cash, and notes for the same amount due November 1 in 1920, 1921, and 1922; Ruppert and Huston assisted Frazee in selling the notes to banks for immediate cash.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The transaction was contingent on Ruth signing a new contract, which was quickly accomplished—Ruth agreed to fulfill the remaining two years on his contract, but was given a $20,000 bonus, payable over two seasons.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The deal was announced on January 6, 1920.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Reaction in Boston was mixed: some fans were embittered at the loss of Ruth; others conceded that Ruth had become difficult to deal with.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] According to Marty Appel in his history of the Yankees, the transaction, "changed the fortunes of two high-profile franchises for decades".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The Red Sox, winners of five of the first 16 World Series, those played between 1903 and 1919, would not win another pennant until 1946, or another World Series until 2004, a drought attributed in baseball superstition to Frazee's sale of Ruth and sometimes dubbed the "Curse of the Bambino".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Conversely, the Yankees had not won the AL championship prior to their acquisition of Ruth.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] They won seven AL pennants and four World Series with him, and lead baseball with 41 pennants and 27 World Series titles in their history.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] When Ruth signed with the Yankees, his transition from a pitcher to a power-hitting outfielder was complete.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] His 15-season Yankee career consisted of over 2,000 games, and Ruth broke many batting records while making only five widely scattered appearances on the mound, winning all of them.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] At the end of April 1920, the Yankees were 4–7, with the Red Sox leading the league with a 10–2 mark.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth had done little, having injured himself swinging the bat.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Both situations began to change on May 1, when Ruth hit a tape measure home run that sent the ball completely out of the Polo Grounds, a feat believed to have been previously accomplished only by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The Yankees won, 6–0, taking three out of four from the Red Sox.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth hit his second home run on May 2, and by the end of the month had set a major league record for home runs in a month with 11, and promptly broke it with 13 in June.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Fans responded with record attendance figures.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] On May 16, Ruth and the Yankees drew 38,600 to the Polo Grounds, a record for the ballpark, and 15,000 fans were turned away.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Large crowds jammed stadiums to see Ruth play when the Yankees were on the road.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth tied his own record of 29 on July 15 and broke it with home runs in both games of a doubleheader four days later.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] By the end of July, he had 37, but his pace slackened somewhat after that.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Nevertheless, on September 4, he both tied and broke the organized baseball record for home runs in a season, snapping Perry Werden's 1895 mark of 44 in the minor Western League.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The Yankees played well as a team, battling for the league lead early in the summer, but slumped in August in the AL pennant battle with Chicago and Cleveland.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The pennant and the World Series were won by Cleveland, who surged ahead after the Black Sox Scandal broke on September 28 and led to the suspension of many of Chicago's top players, including Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The Yankees finished third, but drew 1.2 million fans to the Polo Grounds, the first time a team had drawn a seven-figure attendance.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The rest of the league sold 600,000 more tickets, many fans there to see Ruth, who led the league with 54 home runs, 158 runs, and 137 runs batted in (RBIs).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In 1920 and afterwards, Ruth was aided in his power hitting by the fact that A.J.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Reach Company—the maker of baseballs used in the major leagues—was using a more efficient machine to wind the yarn found within the baseball.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The new baseballs went into play in 1920 and ushered the start of the live-ball era; the number of home runs across the major leagues increased by 184 over the previous year.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Yankees business manager Harry Sparrow had died early in the 1920 season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] Ruppert and Huston hired Barrow to replace him.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] The two men quickly made a deal with Frazee for New York to acquire some of the players who would be mainstays of the early Yankee pennant-winning teams, including catcher Wally Schang and pitcher Waite Hoyt.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p02] In the offseason, Ruth spent some time in Havana, Cuba, where he was said to have lost $35,000 (equivalent to $630,000 in 2025) betting on horse races.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit home runs early and often in the 1921 season, during which he broke Roger Connor's mark for home runs in a career, 138.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Each of the almost 600 home runs Ruth hit in his career after that extended his own record.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] After a slow start, the Yankees were soon locked in a tight pennant race with Cleveland, winners of the 1920 World Series.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On September 15, Ruth hit his 55th home run, breaking his year-old single-season record.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In late September, the Yankees visited Cleveland and won three out of four games, giving them the upper hand in the race, and clinched their first pennant a few days later.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth finished the regular season with 59 home runs, batting .378 and with a slugging percentage of .846.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's 177 runs scored, 119 extra-base hits, and 457 total bases set modern-era records that still stand as of 2024.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees had high expectations when they met the New York Giants in the 1921 World Series, every game of which was played in the Polo Grounds.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees won the first two games with Ruth in the lineup.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] However, Ruth badly scraped his elbow during Game 2 when he slid into third base (he had walked and stolen both second and third bases).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] After the game, he was told by the team physician not to play the rest of the series.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Despite this advice, he did play in the next three games, and pinch-hit in Game Eight of the best-of-nine series, but the Yankees lost, five games to three.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit .316, drove in five runs and hit his first World Series home run.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] After the Series, Ruth and teammates Bob Meusel and Bill Piercy participated in a barnstorming tour in the Northeast.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] A rule then in force prohibited World Series participants from playing in exhibition games during the offseason, the purpose being to prevent Series participants from replicating the Series and undermining its value.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Baseball Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis suspended the trio until May 20, 1922, and fined them their 1921 World Series checks.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In August 1922, the rule was changed to allow limited barnstorming for World Series participants, with Landis's permission required.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On March 4, 1922, Ruth signed a new contract for three years at $52,000 a year (equivalent to $1,000,000 in 2025).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] This was more than two times the largest sum ever paid to a ballplayer up to that point and it represented 40% of the team's player payroll.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Despite his suspension, Ruth was named the Yankees' new on-field captain prior to the 1922 season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] During the suspension, he worked out with the team in the morning and played exhibition games with the Yankees on their off days.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He and Meusel returned on May 20 to a sellout crowd at the Polo Grounds, but Ruth batted 0-for-4 and was booed.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On May 25, he was thrown out of the game for throwing dust in umpire George Hildebrand's face, then climbed into the stands to confront a heckler.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ban Johnson ordered him fined, suspended, and stripped of position as team captain.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In his shortened season, Ruth appeared in 110 games, batted .315, with 35 home runs, and drove in 99 runs, but the 1922 season was a disappointment in comparison to his two previous dominating years.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Despite Ruth's off-year, the Yankees managed to win the pennant and faced the New York Giants in the World Series for the second consecutive year.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In the Series, Giants manager John McGraw instructed his pitchers to throw him nothing but curveballs, and Ruth never adjusted.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth had just two hits in 17 at bats, and the Yankees lost to the Giants for the second straight year, by 4–0 (with one tie game).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Sportswriter Joe Vila called him, "an exploded phenomenon".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] After the season, Ruth was a guest at an Elks Club banquet, set up by Ruth's agent with Yankee team support.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] There, each speaker, concluding with future New York mayor Jimmy Walker, censured him for his poor behavior.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] An emotional Ruth promised reform, and, to the surprise of many, followed through.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] When he reported to spring training, he was in his best shape as a Yankee, weighing only 210 pounds (95 kg).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees' status as tenants of the Giants at the Polo Grounds had become increasingly uneasy, and in 1922, Giants owner Charles Stoneham said the Yankees' lease, expiring after that season, would not be renewed.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruppert and Huston had long contemplated a new stadium, and had taken an option on property at 161st Street and River Avenue in the Bronx.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Yankee Stadium was completed in time for the home opener on April 18, 1923, at which Ruth hit the first home run in what was quickly dubbed "the House that Ruth Built".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The ballpark was designed with Ruth in mind: although the venue's left-field fence was further from home plate than at the Polo Grounds, Yankee Stadium's right-field fence was closer, making home runs easier to hit for left-handed batters.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] To spare Ruth's eyes, right field—his defensive position—was not pointed into the afternoon sun, as was traditional; left fielder Meusel soon developed headaches from squinting toward home plate.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] During the 1923 season, the Yankees were never seriously challenged and won the AL pennant by 17 games.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth finished the season with a career-high .393 batting average and 41 home runs, which tied Cy Williams for the most in the major-leagues that year.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit a career-high 45 doubles in 1923, and he reached base 379 times, then a major league record.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] For the third straight year, the Yankees faced the Giants in the World Series, which Ruth dominated.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He batted .368, walked eight times, scored eight runs, hit three home runs and slugged 1.000 during the series, as the Yankees christened their new stadium with their first World Series championship, four games to two.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In 1924, the Yankees were favored to become the first team to win four consecutive pennants.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Plagued by injuries, they found themselves in a battle with the Senators.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Although the Yankees won 18 of 22 at one point in September, the Senators beat out the Yankees by two games.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit .378, winning his only AL batting title, with a league-leading 46 home runs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth did not look like an athlete; he was described as "toothpicks attached to a piano", with a big upper body but thin wrists and legs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth had kept up his efforts to stay in shape in 1923 and 1924, but by early 1925 weighed nearly 260 pounds (120 kg).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] His annual visit to Hot Springs, Arkansas, where he exercised and took saunas early in the year, did him no good as he spent much of the time carousing in the resort town.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He became ill while there, and relapsed during spring training.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth collapsed in Asheville, North Carolina, as the team journeyed north.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He was put on a train for New York, where he was briefly hospitalized.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] A rumor circulated that he had died, prompting British newspapers to print a premature obituary.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In New York, Ruth collapsed again and was found unconscious in his hotel bathroom.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He was taken to a hospital where he had multiple convulsions.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] McGeehan wrote that Ruth's illness was due to binging on hot dogs and soda pop before a game, it became known as "the bellyache heard 'round the world".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] However, the exact cause of his ailment has never been confirmed and remains a mystery.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Glenn Stout, in his history of the Yankees, writes that the Ruth legend is "still one of the most sheltered in sports"; he suggests that alcohol was at the root of Ruth's illness, pointing to the fact that Ruth remained six weeks at St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Vincent's Hospital but was allowed to leave, under supervision, for workouts with the team for part of that time.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He concludes that the hospitalization was behavior-related.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Playing just 98 games, Ruth had his worst season as a Yankee; he finished with a .290 average and 25 home runs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees finished next to last in the AL with a 69–85 record, their last season with a losing record until 1965.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth spent part of the offseason of 1925–26 working out at Artie McGovern's gym, where he got back into shape.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Barrow and Huggins had rebuilt the team and surrounded the veteran core with good young players like Tony Lazzeri and Lou Gehrig, but the Yankees were not expected to win the pennant.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth returned to his normal production during 1926, when he batted .372 with 47 home runs and 146 RBIs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees built a 10-game lead by mid-June and coasted to win the pennant by three games.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Louis Cardinals had won the National League with the lowest winning percentage for a pennant winner to that point (.578) and the Yankees were expected to win the World Series easily.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Although the Yankees won the opener in New York, St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In Game Four, Ruth hit three home runs—the first time this had been done in a World Series game—to lead the Yankees to victory.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In the fifth game, Ruth caught a ball as he crashed into the fence.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The play was described by baseball writers as a defensive gem.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] New York took that game, but Grover Cleveland Alexander won Game Six for St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Louis to tie the Series at three games each, then got very drunk.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He was nevertheless inserted into Game Seven in the seventh inning and shut down the Yankees to win the game, 3–2, and win the Series.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth had hit his fourth home run of the Series earlier in the game and was the only Yankee to reach base off Alexander; he walked in the ninth inning before being thrown out to end the game when he attempted to steal second base.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Although Ruth's attempt to steal second is often deemed a baserunning blunder, Creamer pointed out that the Yankees' chances of tying the game would have been greatly improved with a runner in scoring position.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The 1926 World Series was also known for Ruth's promise to Johnny Sylvester, a hospitalized 11-year-old boy.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth promised the child that he would hit a home run on his behalf.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Sylvester had been injured in a fall from a horse, and a friend of Sylvester's father gave the boy two autographed baseballs signed by Yankees and Cardinals.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The friend relayed a promise from Ruth (who did not know the boy) that he would hit a home run for him.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] After the Series, Ruth visited the boy in the hospital.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] When the matter became public, the press greatly inflated it, and by some accounts, Ruth allegedly saved the boy's life by visiting him, emotionally promising to hit a home run, and doing so.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's 1926 salary of $52,000 was far more than any other baseball player, but he made at least twice as much in other income, including $100,000 from 12 weeks of vaudeville.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The 1927 New York Yankees team is considered one of the greatest squads to ever take the field.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Known as Murderers' Row because of the power of its lineup, the team clinched first place on Labor Day, won a then-AL-record 110 games and took the AL pennant by 19 games.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] There was no suspense in the pennant race, and the nation turned its attention to Ruth's pursuit of his own single-season home run record of 59 round trippers.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Teammate Lou Gehrig proved to be a slugger who was capable of challenging Ruth for his home run crown; he tied Ruth with 24 home runs late in June.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Through July and August, the dynamic duo was never separated by more than two home runs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Gehrig took the lead, 45–44, in the first game of a doubleheader at Fenway Park early in September; Ruth responded with two blasts of his own to take the lead, as it proved permanently—Gehrig finished with 47.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Even so, as of September 6, Ruth was still several games off his 1921 pace, and going into the final series against the Senators, had only 57.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He hit two in the first game of the series, including one off of Paul Hopkins, facing his first major league batter, to tie the record.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The following day, September 30, he broke it with his 60th homer, in the eighth inning off Tom Zachary to break a 2–2 tie.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Let's see some son of a bitch try to top that one", Ruth exulted after the game.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In addition to his career-high 60 home runs, Ruth batted .356, drove in 164 runs and slugged .772.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In the 1927 World Series, the Yankees swept the Pittsburgh Pirates in four games; the National Leaguers were disheartened after watching the Yankees take batting practice before Game One, with ball after ball leaving Forbes Field.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] According to Appel, "The 1927 New York Yankees.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The following season started off well for the Yankees, who led the league in the early going.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] But the Yankees were plagued by injuries, erratic pitching and inconsistent play.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Philadelphia Athletics, rebuilding after some lean years, erased the Yankees' big lead and even took over first place briefly in early September.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees, however, regained first place when they beat the Athletics three out of four games in a pivotal series at Yankee Stadium later that month, and clinched the pennant in the final weekend of the season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's play in 1928 mirrored his team's performance.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He got off to a hot start and on August 1, he had 42 home runs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] This put him ahead of his 60 home run pace from the previous season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He then slumped for the latter part of the season, and he hit just twelve home runs in the last two months.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's batting average also fell to .323, well below his career average.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Nevertheless, he ended the season with 54 home runs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees swept the favored Cardinals in four games in the World Series, with Ruth batting .625 and hitting three home runs in Game Four, including one off Alexander.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Before the 1929 season, Ruppert (who had bought out Huston in 1923) announced that the Yankees would wear uniform numbers to allow fans at cavernous Yankee Stadium to easily identify the players.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Cardinals and Indians had each experimented with uniform numbers; the Yankees were the first to use them on both home and away uniforms.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth batted third and was given number 3.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] According to a long-standing baseball legend, the Yankees adopted their now-iconic pinstriped uniforms in hopes of making Ruth look slimmer.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In truth, though, they had been wearing pinstripes since 1915.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Although the Yankees started well, the Athletics soon proved they were the better team in 1929, splitting two series with the Yankees in the first month of the season, then taking advantage of a Yankee losing streak in mid-May to gain first place.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Although Ruth performed well, the Yankees were not able to catch the Athletics—Connie Mack had built another great team.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Tragedy struck the Yankees late in the year when manager Huggins died at 51 of erysipelas, a bacterial skin infection, on September 25, only ten days after he had last directed the team.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Despite their past differences, Ruth praised Huggins and described him as a "great guy".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees finished second, 18 games behind the Athletics.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit .345 during the season, with 46 home runs and 154 RBIs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On October 17, the Yankees hired Bob Shawkey as manager; he was their fourth choice.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth had politicked for the job of player-manager, but Ruppert and Barrow never seriously considered him for the position.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Stout deemed this the first hint Ruth would have no future with the Yankees once he retired as a player.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Shawkey, a former Yankees player and teammate of Ruth, would prove unable to command Ruth's respect.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On January 7, 1930, salary negotiations between the Yankees and Ruth quickly broke down.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] When asked why he thought he was "worth more than the President of the United States," Ruth responded: "Say, if I hadn't been sick last summer, I'd have broken hell out of that home run record!
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Besides, the President gets a four-year contract.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] I'm only asking for three." Exactly two months later, a compromise was reached, with Ruth settling for two years at an unprecedented $80,000 per year.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's salary was more than 2.4 times greater than the next-highest salary that season, a record margin as of 2025.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In 1930, Ruth hit .359 with 49 home runs (his best in his years after 1928) and 153 RBIs, and pitched his first game in nine years, a complete game victory.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Nevertheless, the Athletics won their second consecutive pennant and World Series, as the Yankees finished in third place, sixteen games back.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] At the end of the season, Shawkey was fired and replaced with Cubs manager Joe McCarthy, though Ruth again unsuccessfully sought the job.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] McCarthy was a disciplinarian, but chose not to interfere with Ruth, who did not seek conflict with the manager.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The team improved in 1931, but was no match for the Athletics, who won 107 games, 13+1⁄2 games in front of the Yankees.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth, for his part, hit .373, with 46 home runs and 163 RBIs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In the 1932 season, the Yankees went 107–47 and won the pennant.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's effectiveness had decreased somewhat, but he still hit .341 with 41 home runs and 137 RBIs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Nevertheless, he was sidelined twice because of injuries during the season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees faced the Cubs, McCarthy's former team, in the 1932 World Series.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] There was bad blood between the two teams as the Yankees resented the Cubs only awarding half a World Series share to Mark Koenig, a former Yankee.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The games at Yankee Stadium had not been sellouts; both were won by the home team, with Ruth collecting two singles, but scoring four runs as he was walked four times by the Cubs pitchers.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In Chicago, Ruth was resentful at the hostile crowds that met the Yankees' train and jeered them at the hotel.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The crowd for Game Three included New York Governor Franklin D.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Roosevelt, the Democratic candidate for president, who sat with Chicago Mayor Anton Cermak.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Many in the crowd threw lemons at Ruth, a sign of derision, and others (as well as the Cubs themselves) shouted abuse at Ruth and other Yankees.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] They were briefly silenced when Ruth hit a three-run home run off Charlie Root in the first inning, but soon revived, and the Cubs tied the score at 4–4 in the fourth inning, partly due to Ruth's fielding error in the outfield.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] When Ruth came to the plate in the top of the fifth, the Chicago crowd and players, led by pitcher Guy Bush, were screaming insults at Ruth.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] With the count at two balls and one strike, Ruth gestured, possibly in the direction of center field, and after the next pitch (a strike), may have pointed there with one hand.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit the fifth pitch over the center field fence; estimates were that it traveled nearly 500 feet (150 m).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Whether or not Ruth intended to indicate where he planned to (and did) hit the ball (Charlie Devens, who, in 1999, was interviewed as Ruth's surviving teammate in that game, did not think so), the incident has gone down in legend as Babe Ruth's called shot.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees won Game Three, and the following day clinched the Series with another victory.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] During that game, Bush hit Ruth on the arm with a pitch, causing words to be exchanged and provoking a game-winning Yankee rally.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He batted .301, with 34 home runs, 103 RBIs, and a league-leading 114 walks, as the Yankees finished in second place, seven games behind the Senators.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Athletics manager Connie Mack selected him to play right field in the first Major League Baseball All-Star Game, held on July 6, 1933, at Comiskey Park in Chicago.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He hit the first home run in the All-Star Game's history, a two-run blast against Bill Hallahan during the third inning, which helped the AL win the game 4–2.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] During the final game of the 1933 season, as a publicity stunt organized by his team, Ruth was called upon and pitched a complete game victory against the Red Sox, his final appearance as a pitcher.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Despite unremarkable pitching numbers, Ruth had a 5–0 record in five games for the Yankees, raising his career totals to 94–46.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In 1934, Ruth played in his last full season with the Yankees.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] By this time, years of high living were starting to catch up with him.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] His conditioning had deteriorated to the point that he could no longer field or run.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He accepted a pay cut to $35,000 from Ruppert, but he was still the highest-paid player in the major leagues.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He could still handle a bat, recording a .288 batting average with 22 home runs, and on July 13, 1934, he hit his 700th career home run.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] However, Reisler described these statistics as "merely mortal" by Ruth's previous standards.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth was selected to the AL All-Star team for the second consecutive year, even though he was in the twilight of his career.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] During the game, New York Giants pitcher Carl Hubbell struck out Ruth and four other future Hall-of-Famers consecutively.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees finished second again, seven games behind the Tigers.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] By this time, Ruth knew he was nearly finished as a player.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He desired to remain in baseball as a manager.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He was often spoken of as a possible candidate as managerial jobs opened up, but in 1932, when he was mentioned as a contender for the Red Sox position, Ruth stated that he was not yet ready to leave the field.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] There were rumors that Ruth was a likely candidate each time when the Cleveland Indians, Cincinnati Reds, and Detroit Tigers were looking for a manager, but nothing came of them.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Just before the 1934 season, Ruppert offered to make Ruth the manager of the Yankees' top minor-league team, the Newark Bears, but he was talked out of it by his wife, Claire, and his business manager, Christy Walsh.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Tigers owner Frank Navin seriously considered acquiring Ruth and making him player-manager.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] However, Ruth insisted on delaying the meeting until he came back from a trip to Hawaii.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth opted to go on his trip, despite Barrow advising him that he was making a mistake; in any event, Ruth's asking price was too high for the notoriously tight-fisted Navin.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Tigers' job ultimately went to Mickey Cochrane.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Early in the 1934 season, Ruth made no secret of his desire to manage the Yankees.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] However, that job was never a serious possibility.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruppert always supported McCarthy, who would remain in his position for another 12 seasons.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The relationship between Ruth and McCarthy had been lukewarm at best, and Ruth's open campaigning to replace him further chilled their interpersonal relations.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] By the end of the season, Ruth hinted that he would retire unless Ruppert named him manager of the Yankees.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] When the time came, Ruppert wanted Ruth to leave the team without drama or hard feelings.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] During the 1934–35 offseason, Ruth circled the world with his wife; the trip included a barnstorming tour of the Far East.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] At his final stop in the United Kingdom before returning home, Ruth was introduced to cricket by Australian player Alan Fairfax, and after having little luck in a cricketer's stance, he stood as a baseball batter and launched some massive shots around the field, destroying the bat in the process.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Although Fairfax regretted that he could not have the time to make Ruth a cricket player, Ruth had lost any interest in such a career upon learning that the best batsmen made only about $40 per week.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Also during the offseason, Ruppert had been sounding out the other clubs in hopes of finding one that would be willing to take Ruth as a manager or player.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] However, the only serious offer came from Athletics owner-manager Connie Mack, who gave some thought to stepping down as manager in favor of Ruth.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] However, Mack later dropped the idea, saying that Ruth's wife would be running the team in a month if Ruth ever took over.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] While the barnstorming tour was underway, Ruppert began negotiating with Boston Braves owner Judge Emil Fuchs, who wanted Ruth as a gate attraction.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Braves had enjoyed modest recent success, finishing fourth in the National League in both 1933 and 1934, but the team drew poorly at the box office.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Unable to afford the rent at Braves Field, Fuchs had considered holding dog races there when the Braves were not at home, only to be turned down by Landis.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] After a series of phone calls, letters, and meetings, the Yankees traded Ruth to the Braves on February 26, 1935.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruppert had stated that he would not release Ruth to go to another team as a full-time player.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] For this reason, it was announced that Ruth would become a team vice president and would be consulted on all club transactions, in addition to playing.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He was also made assistant manager to Braves skipper Bill McKechnie.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In a long letter to Ruth a few days before the press conference, Fuchs promised Ruth a share in the Braves' profits, with the possibility of becoming co-owner of the team.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Fuchs also raised the possibility of Ruth succeeding McKechnie as manager, perhaps as early as 1936.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruppert called the deal "the greatest opportunity Ruth ever had".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] There was considerable attention as Ruth reported for spring training.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He did not hit his first home run of the spring until after the team had left Florida, and was beginning the road north in Savannah.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He hit two in an exhibition game against the Bears.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Amid much press attention, Ruth played his first home game in Boston in over 16 years.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Before an opening-day crowd of over 25,000, including five of New England's six state governors, Ruth accounted for all the Braves' runs in a 4–2 win over the New York Giants, hitting a two-run home run, singling to drive in a third run and later in the inning scoring the fourth.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Although age and weight had slowed him, he made a running catch in left field that sportswriters deemed the defensive highlight of the game.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth had two hits in the second game of the season, but it quickly went downhill both for him and the Braves from there.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The season soon settled down to a routine of Ruth performing poorly on the few occasions he even played at all.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] As April passed into May, Ruth's physical deterioration became even more pronounced.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] While he remained productive at the plate early on, he could do little else.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] His conditioning had become so poor that he could barely trot around the bases.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He made so many errors that three Braves pitchers told McKechnie they would not take the mound if he was in the lineup.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Before long, Ruth stopped hitting as well.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He grew increasingly annoyed that McKechnie ignored most of his advice.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] McKechnie later said that Ruth's presence made enforcing discipline nearly impossible.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth soon realized that Fuchs had deceived him, and had no intention of making him manager or giving him any significant off-field duties.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He later said his only duties as vice president consisted of making public appearances and autographing tickets.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth also found out that far from giving him a share of the profits, Fuchs wanted him to invest some of *his* money in the team in a last-ditch effort to improve its balance sheet.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] As it turned out, Fuchs and Ruppert had both known all along that Ruth's non-playing positions were meaningless.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] By the end of the first month of the season, Ruth concluded he was finished even as a part-time player.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] As early as May 12, he asked Fuchs to let him retire.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ultimately, Fuchs persuaded Ruth to remain at least until after the Memorial Day doubleheader in Philadelphia.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In the interim was a western road trip, at which the rival teams had scheduled days to honor him.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Louis, Ruth performed poorly, and his batting average sank to .155, with only two additional home runs for a total of three on the season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In the first two games in Pittsburgh, Ruth had only one hit, though a long fly caught by Paul Waner probably would have been a home run in any other ballpark besides Forbes Field.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth played in the third game of the Pittsburgh series on May 25, 1935, and added one more tale to his playing legend.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth went 4-for-4, including three home runs, though the Braves lost the game 11–7.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The last two were off Ruth's old Cubs nemesis, Guy Bush.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The final home run, both of the game and of Ruth's career, sailed out of the park over the right field upper deck–the first time anyone had hit a fair ball completely out of Forbes Field.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth was urged to make this his last game, but he had given his word to Fuchs to stay on through Memorial Day and played in Cincinnati and Philadelphia.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The first game of the doubleheader in Philadelphia—the Braves lost both—would be his final major league appearance.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth retired on June 2 after an argument with Fuchs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He finished 1935 with a .181 average—easily his worst as a full-time position player—and the final six of his 714 home runs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The Braves, 10–27 when Ruth left, finished 38–115, at .248 the worst winning percentage in modern National League history.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Insolvent like his team, Fuchs gave up control of the Braves before the end of the season; the National League took over the franchise at the end of the year.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] At the time of his retirement, Ruth held many baseball batting records.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] These include the career records for home runs (714), slugging percentage (0.690), runs batted in (2,213), bases on balls (2,062) and on-base percentage (.474).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He still remains in the top ten of many statistical rankings.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Although Fuchs had given Ruth his unconditional release, no major league team expressed an interest in hiring him in any capacity.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth still hoped to be hired as a manager if he could not play anymore, but only one managerial position, Cleveland, became available between Ruth's retirement and the end of the 1937 season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Asked if he had considered Ruth for the job, Indians owner Alva Bradley replied negatively.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Of the five members in the inaugural class of Baseball Hall of Fame in 1936 (Ty Cobb, Honus Wagner, Christy Mathewson, Walter Johnson and Ruth), only Ruth was not given an offer to manage a baseball team.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The author believed there was not necessarily a relationship between personal conduct and managerial success, noting that John McGraw, Billy Martin, and Bobby Valentine were winners despite character flaws.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth played much golf and in a few exhibition baseball games, where he demonstrated a continuing ability to draw large crowds.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] This appeal contributed to the Dodgers hiring him as first base coach in 1938.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] When Ruth was hired, Brooklyn general manager Larry MacPhail made it clear that Ruth would not be considered for the manager's job if, as expected, Burleigh Grimes retired at the end of the season.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Although much was said about what Ruth could teach the younger players, in practice, his duties were to appear on the field in uniform and encourage base runners—he was not called upon to relay signs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In August, shortly before the baseball rosters expanded, Ruth sought an opportunity to return as an active player in a pinch hitting role.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth often took batting practice before games and felt that he could take on the limited role.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Grimes denied his request, citing Ruth's poor vision in his right eye, his inability to run the bases, and the risk of an injury to Ruth.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth got along well with everyone except team captain Leo Durocher, who was hired as Grimes' replacement at season's end.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth then left his job as a first base coach and would never again work in any capacity in the game of baseball.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On July 4, 1939, Ruth spoke on Lou Gehrig Appreciation Day at Yankee Stadium as members of the 1927 Yankees and a sellout crowd turned out to honor the first baseman, who was forced into premature retirement by ALS, which would kill him two years later.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The next week, Ruth went to Cooperstown, New York, for the formal opening of the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Three years earlier, he was one of the first five players elected to the hall.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] As radio broadcasts of baseball games became popular, Ruth sought a job in that field, arguing that his celebrity and knowledge of baseball would assure large audiences, but he received no offers.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] During World War II, he made many personal appearances to advance the war effort, including his last appearance as a player at Yankee Stadium, in a 1943 exhibition for the Army-Navy Relief Fund.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He hit a long fly ball off Walter Johnson; the blast left the field, curving foul, but Ruth circled the bases anyway.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In 1946, he made a final effort to gain a job in baseball when he contacted new Yankees boss MacPhail, but he was sent a rejection letter.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In 1999, Ruth's granddaughter, Linda Tosetti, and his daughter, Julia Ruth Stevens, said that Babe's inability to land a managerial role with the Yankees caused him to feel hurt and slump into a severe depression.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth started playing golf when he was 20 and continued playing the game throughout his life.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] His appearance at many New York courses drew spectators and headlines.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Rye Golf Club was among the courses he played with teammate Lyn Lary in June 1933.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] With birdies on 3 holes, Ruth posted the best score.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In retirement, he became one of the first celebrity golfers participating in charity tournaments, including one where he was pitted against Ty Cobb.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth met Helen Woodford, by some accounts, in a coffee shop in Boston, where she was a waitress.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] They married as teenagers on October 17, 1914.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Although Ruth later claimed to have been married in Elkton, Maryland, records show that they were married at St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Paul's Catholic Church in Ellicott City.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] They adopted a daughter, Dorothy, in 1921.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth and Helen separated around 1925 reportedly because of Ruth's repeated infidelities and neglect.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] They appeared in public as a couple for the last time during the 1926 World Series.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Helen died in January 1929 at age 31 in a fire in a house in Watertown, Massachusetts owned by Edward Kinder, a dentist with whom she had been living as "Mrs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In her book, *My Dad, the Babe*, Dorothy claimed that she was Ruth's biological child by a mistress named Juanita Jennings.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In 1980, Juanita, who was at the time very ill, admitted this to Dorothy and Dorothy's sister, Julia.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On April 17, 1929, three months after the death of his first wife, Ruth married actress and model Claire Merritt Hodgson and adopted her daughter Julia.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] It was the second and final marriage for both parties.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Claire was well-travelled and educated, and put structure into Ruth's life, like Miller Huggins did for him on the field.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] By one account, Julia and Dorothy were, through no fault of their own, the reason for the seven-year rift in Ruth's relationship with teammate Lou Gehrig.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Sometime in 1932, during a conversation that she assumed was private, Gehrig's mother remarked, "It's a shame [Claire] doesn't dress Dorothy as nicely as she dresses her own daughter." When the comment got back to Ruth, he angrily told Gehrig to tell his mother to mind her own business.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Gehrig, in turn, took offense at what he perceived as Ruth's comment about his mother.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The two men reportedly never spoke off the field until they reconciled at Yankee Stadium on Lou Gehrig Appreciation Day, July 4, 1939, shortly after Gehrig's retirement from baseball.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] They're too much fun." A detective that the Yankees hired to follow him one night in Chicago reported that Ruth had been with six women.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ping Bodie said that he was not Ruth's roommate while traveling; "I room with his suitcase".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Before the start of the 1922 season, Ruth had signed a three-year contract at $52,000 per year (equivalent to $1,000,000 in 2025) with an option to renew for two additional years.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] His performance during the 1922 season had been disappointing, attributed in part to his drinking and late-night hours.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] After the end of the 1922 season, he was asked to sign a contract addendum with a morals clause.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth and Ruppert signed it on November 11, 1922.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] It called for Ruth to abstain entirely from the use of intoxicating liquors, and to not stay up later than 1:00 a.m. during the training and playing season without permission of the manager.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth was also enjoined from any action or misbehavior that would compromise his ability to play baseball.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In 1928, Ruth campaigned for Democratic U.S. presidential nominee Al Smith.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] As early as the war years, doctors had cautioned Ruth to take better care of his health, and he grudgingly followed their advice, limiting his drinking and not going on a proposed trip to support the troops in the South Pacific.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In 1946, Ruth began experiencing severe pain over his left eye and had difficulty swallowing.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In November 1946, Ruth entered French Hospital in New York for tests, which revealed that he had an inoperable malignant tumor at the base of his skull and in his neck.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The malady was a lesion known as nasopharyngeal carcinoma, or lymphoepithelioma.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] A physician who reviewed Ruth's autopsy in 1998 concluded that Ruth's lifelong use of tobacco "probably played a part" in his cancer.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] His name and fame gave him access to experimental treatments, and he was one of the first cancer patients to receive both drugs and radiation treatment simultaneously.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Having lost 80 pounds (36 kg), he was discharged from the hospital in February and went to Florida to recuperate.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He returned to New York and Yankee Stadium after the season started.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The new commissioner, Happy Chandler (Judge Landis had died in 1944), proclaimed April 27, 1947, Babe Ruth Day around the major leagues, with the most significant observance to be at Yankee Stadium.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] A number of teammates and others spoke in honor of Ruth, who briefly addressed the crowd of almost 60,000.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] By then, his voice was a soft whisper with a very low, raspy tone.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Around this time, developments in chemotherapy offered some hope for Ruth.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The doctors had not told Ruth he had cancer because of his family's fear that he might do himself harm.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] They treated him with pterolyl triglutamate (Teropterin), a folic acid derivative; he may have been the first human subject.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth showed dramatic improvement during the summer of 1947, so much so that his case was presented by his doctors at a scientific meeting, without using his name.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He was able to travel around the country, doing promotional work for the Ford Motor Company on American Legion Baseball.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He appeared again at another day in his honor at Yankee Stadium in September, but was not well enough to pitch in an old-timers game as he had hoped.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The improvement was only a temporary remission, and by late 1947, Ruth was unable to help with the writing of his autobiography, *The Babe Ruth Story*, which was almost entirely ghostwritten.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In and out of the hospital in Manhattan, he left for Florida in February 1948, doing what activities he could.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] After six weeks he returned to New York to appear at a book-signing party.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He also traveled to California to witness the filming of the movie based on the book.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On June 5, 1948, a "gaunt and hollowed-out" Ruth visited Yale University to donate a manuscript of *The Babe Ruth Story* to its library.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] At Yale, he met with future president George H.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Bush, who was the captain of the Yale baseball team.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On June 13, Ruth visited Yankee Stadium for the final time in his life, appearing at the 25th-anniversary celebrations of "The House that Ruth Built".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] By this time he had lost much weight and had difficulty walking.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Introduced along with his surviving teammates from 1923, Ruth used a bat as a cane.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Nat Fein's photo of Ruth taken from behind, standing near home plate and facing "Ruthville" (right field) became one of baseball's most famous and widely circulated photographs, and won the Pulitzer Prize.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth made one final trip on behalf of American Legion Baseball.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He then entered Memorial Hospital, where he would die.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He was never told he had cancer; however, before his death, he surmised it.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He was able to leave the hospital for a few short trips, including a final visit to Baltimore.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On July 26, 1948, Ruth left the hospital to attend the premiere of the film *The Babe Ruth Story*.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Shortly thereafter, he returned to the hospital for the final time.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's condition gradually grew worse, and only a few visitors were permitted to see him, one of whom was National League president and future Commissioner of Baseball Ford C.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] He had been such a big man and his arms were just skinny little bones, and his face was so haggard", Frick said years later.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Thousands of New Yorkers, including many children, stood vigil outside the hospital during Ruth's final days.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On August 16, 1948, at 8:01 p.m., Ruth died in his sleep at the age of 53.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] His funeral service took place over three days.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] His open casket was placed on display in the rotunda of Yankee Stadium, where it remained for two days; 77,000 people filed past to pay him tribute.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] His Requiem Mass was celebrated by Francis Cardinal Spellman at St.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Patrick's Cathedral; a crowd estimated at 75,000 waited outside.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth is buried with his second wife, Claire, on a hillside in Section 25 at the Gate of Heaven Cemetery in Hawthorne, New York.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] On April 19, 1949, the Yankees unveiled a granite monument in Ruth's honor in center field of Yankee Stadium.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The monument was located in the field of play next to a flagpole and similar tributes to Huggins and Gehrig until the stadium was remodeled from 1974 to 1975, which resulted in the outfield fences moving inward and enclosing the monuments from the playing field.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] This area was known thereafter as Monument Park.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Yankee Stadium, "the House that Ruth Built", was replaced after the 2008 season with a new Yankee Stadium across the street from the old one; Monument Park was subsequently moved to the new venue behind the center field fence.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's uniform number 3 has been retired by the Yankees, and he is one of five Yankees players or managers to have a granite monument within the stadium.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] In 1974, Ruth's birthplace in Baltimore was renovated and opened to the public as the Babe Ruth Birthplace and Museum.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] The museum houses a collection of artifacts from Ruth's life, including some rare baseball cards and the earliest known signature of Ruth, from when he was still pitching in the schoolyard.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's widow, Claire, his two daughters, Dorothy and Julia, and his sister, Mamie, helped select and install exhibits for the museum.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth was the first baseball star to be the subject of overwhelming public adulation.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Baseball had been known for star players such as Ty Cobb and "Shoeless Joe" Jackson, but both men had uneasy relations with fans.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In Cobb's case, the incidents were sometimes marked by violence.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth's biographers agreed that he benefited from the timing of his ascension to "Home Run King".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] The country had been hit hard by both the war and the 1918 flu pandemic and longed for something to help put these traumas behind it.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth also resonated in a country which felt, in the aftermath of the war, that it took second place to no one.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Montville argued that Ruth was a larger-than-life figure who was capable of unprecedented athletic feats in the nation's largest city.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth became an icon of the social changes that marked the early 1920s.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In his history of the Yankees, Glenn Stout writes that "Ruth was New York incarnate—uncouth and raw, flamboyant and flashy, oversized, out of scale, and absolutely unstoppable".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] During his lifetime, Ruth became a symbol of the United States.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] During World War II, Japanese soldiers yelled in English, "To hell with Babe Ruth", to anger American soldiers.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth replied that he hoped "every Jap that mention[ed] my name gets shot".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Creamer recorded that "Babe Ruth transcended sport and moved far beyond the artificial limits of baselines and outfield fences and sports pages".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Wagenheim stated, "He appealed to a deeply rooted American yearning for the definitive climax: clean, quick, unarguable." According to Glenn Stout, "Ruth's home runs were [an] exalted, uplifting experience that meant more to fans than any runs they were responsible for.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Although Ruth was not just a power hitter—he was the Yankees' best bunter, and an excellent outfielder—Ruth's penchant for hitting home runs altered how baseball is played.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Prior to 1920, home runs were unusual, and managers tried to win games by getting a runner on base and bringing him around to score through such means as the stolen base, the bunt, and the hit and run.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Advocates of what was dubbed "inside baseball", such as Giants manager McGraw, disliked the home run, considering it a blot on the purity of the game.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Phelon, after the 1920 season, Ruth's breakout performance that season and the response in excitement and attendance, "settled, for all time to come, that the American public is nuttier over the Home Run than the Clever Fielding or the Hitless Pitching.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] According to sportswriter Grantland Rice, only two sports figures of the 1920s approached Ruth in popularity—boxer Jack Dempsey and racehorse Man o' War.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] One of the factors that contributed to Ruth's broad appeal was the uncertainty about his family and early life.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth appeared to exemplify the American success story, that even an uneducated, unsophisticated youth, without any family wealth or connections, can do something better than anyone else in the world.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Montville writes that "the fog [surrounding his childhood] will make him forever accessible, universal.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] He will be the patron saint of American possibility." Similarly, the fact that Ruth played in the pre-television era, when a relatively small portion of his fans had the opportunity to see him play, allowed his legend to grow through word of mouth and the hyperbole of sports reporters.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Reisler states that recent sluggers who surpassed Ruth's 60-home run mark, such as Mark McGwire and Barry Bonds, generated much less excitement than when Ruth repeatedly broke the single-season home run record in the 1920s.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth dominated a relatively small sports world, while Americans of the present era have many sports available to watch.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Thomas Barthel describes Ruth as one of the first celebrity athletes; numerous biographies have portrayed him as "larger than life".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] A dominant figure in a field is often referred to as "the Babe Ruth" of that field.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] He was the first athlete to make more money from endorsements and off-the-field activities than from his sport.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In 2006, Montville stated that more books have been written about Ruth than any other member of the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] The long ball era that Ruth started continues in baseball: owners build ballparks to encourage home runs.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In various rankings, Ruth has been named the greatest baseball player of all time.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In 1998, *The Sporting News* ranked him number one on the list of "Baseball's 100 Greatest Players".
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In 1999, baseball fans named Ruth to the Major League Baseball All-Century Team.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] He was named baseball's Greatest Player Ever in a 1969 ballot.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] The Associated Press reported in 1993 that Muhammad Ali was tied with Babe Ruth as the most recognized athlete in America.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In 1999, the Associated Press named Ruth the greatest athlete of the 20th century, while an ESPN poll ranked him the second-greatest North American athlete of the century.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In 1983, the United States Postal Service honored Ruth with a twenty-cent stamp.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In 2022, *The Sporting News* named Ruth on their "New York Mount Rushmore of Sports", while ESPN ranked him as the greatest baseball player ever that same year.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Several of the most expensive items of sports memorabilia ever sold at auction are associated with Ruth.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] The jersey Ruth wore when hitting his "called shot" home run in the 1932 World Series sold in 2024 for a record $24 million.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] A Ruth 1920 Yankees jersey that sold for $4.4 million in 2012 (equivalent to $6.2 million in 2025) was, for several years, one of the most expensive piece of sports memorabilia ever sold.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] The bat with which he hit the first home run at Yankee Stadium is in *The Guinness Book of World Records* as the most expensive baseball bat sold at auction, having fetched $1.265 million in 2004 (equivalent to $2.1563 million in 2025).
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] Other bats used by Ruth sold for $1.6 million in 2022 and $1.85 million in 2023.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] A hat of Ruth's from the 1934 season set a record for a baseball cap when David Wells sold it at auction for $537 thousand in 2012.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In 2017, Charlie Sheen sold Ruth's 1927 World Series ring for $2 million, a record for a championship ring.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] One lasting legacy of the craze over Ruth may be the Baby Ruth candy bar.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] The original company to market the confectionery, the Curtiss Candy Company, maintained that the bar was named after Ruth Cleveland, daughter of president Grover Cleveland.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] She died in 1904 and the bar was first marketed in 1921, at the height of the craze over Ruth.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] He later sought to market candy bearing his name; he was refused a trademark because of the Baby Ruth bar.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] The Ruth estate licensed his likeness for use in an advertising campaign for Baby Ruth in 1995.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In 2005, Baby Ruth became the official candy bar of Major League Baseball.
[src:outfielder/babe-ruth-p04] In 2018, Ruth was posthumously awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by President Donald Trump; his grandson Tom Stevens accepted the award on his behalf.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] Quick retrieval of loose balls and delivery of the game balls to the servers are necessary for quick play in tennis.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] In professional tournaments, every court will have a trained squad of ball boys/girls with positionings and movements designed for maximum efficiency, while also not interfering with active play.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] As well as dealing with the game balls, ball boys/girls may also provide the players with other assistance, such as the delivery of towels and drinks.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] There are various methods for selecting the ball boys and girls for a tournament.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] In many tournaments, such as Wimbledon and the Queen's Club Championships, they are picked from or apply through schools, where they are selected by tournaments, and they have to go through a number of selections and tests.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] In some other tournaments, such as the Nottingham Open, Australian Open and the US Open, positions are advertised and there are open try-outs.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] Applicants are required to pass a physical ability assessment.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] In addition to fitness and stamina, the abilities to concentrate and remain alert are essential.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] In 2006, the IFAB Laws of the Game of association football were changed to allow multiple balls to be used under the direction of a referee.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] Higher level organised matches now commonly use 6+ balls with ball boys scattered around the pitch to quicken the pace of play.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] Typically positioned behind advertising boards surrounding the pitch, ball boys will try to be in possession of a spare ball at all times, so that this can be given to the players prior to the loose ball being retrieved.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] Balls may also be stored on cones near sidelines, so that they are readily available for restarts, and to prevent ball boys from accelerating returns to home players, and delaying returns to away players.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] Methods for selecting ball boys vary between grounds.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] On occasion, away teams have complained about perceived favour of ball boys towards home sides.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] In a 2013 EFL Cup match Eden Hazard, a member of the away team, which was trailing at the time, got into an altercation with an apparently time-wasting ball boy who was lying on top of the ball.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] Hazard was subsequently sent off for violent conduct and suspended for three games.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] Ball kids are stationed in out-of-play areas near the first and third base foul lines to retrieve out-of-play baseballs.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] They should not be confused with bat boys and bat girls, who remain in or near a team's dugout and the home plate area, primarily to tend to a team's baseball bats.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] As ball kids are stationed on the field, albeit in foul territory, they can occasionally interfere with play; such events are governed by Rule 6.01(d), the main point of which is that if the interference is unintentional, any live ball remains alive and in play.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] For this reason, most teams will use experienced individuals who understand the rules, to minimize mistaken interference.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] One of the more infamous examples was the use of a Hooters girl as a promotion.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] The woman unfortunately snagged a ball that was fair and live in a Tampa Bay Rays game, throwing it to the fans.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] The batter was awarded a double on the interference.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] Since 1992, the San Francisco Giants have employed older men as "balldudes", instead of the traditional youths.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] In 1993, Corinne Mullane became the first "balldudette", and she and her daughter Molly, who began working as a balldudette in the 2000s, have since been included in the National Baseball Hall of Fame as the first mother-daughter ball-retrieving duo in baseball.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] Ball boys are stationed around the field just outside the boundary to retrieve any balls struck into the spectator stands or to the boundary rope.
[src:outfielder/ball-boy] In India, disabled people are not allowed to be ball-boys anymore after a controversy occurred in 2017, after criticism of the Board of Control for Cricket in India surrounding the appearance of a polio-afflicted fan who had been serving as a ball-boy for a few years.
[src:outfielder/base-running] In baseball, **base running** is the act of running from base to base, performed by members of the team at bat.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Base running is a tactical part of the game with the goal of eventually reaching home base (home plate) to score a run.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Batters strive to become base runners, and to enable existing base runners to move to a subsequent base or to score.
[src:outfielder/base-running] In statistics, the number of baserunners (for example those allowed by a pitcher) is denoted by the abbreviation **BR**.
[src:outfielder/base-running] The Official Baseball Rules uses the term **batter-runner** to identify the batter from the time he becomes a base runner until the end of the same play, whether he is successful at legally attaining first base or any subsequent base.
[src:outfielder/base-running] The term is not applied if the batter is awarded first base (the last three items in the above list).
[src:outfielder/base-running] If a base runner's teammate is put out for the third out of the inning, the base runner is said to be left on base (LOB).
[src:outfielder/base-running] A runner who is touching a base which he is entitled to occupy may not be tagged out.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Runners may attempt to advance from base to base on any fair ball that touches the ground.
[src:outfielder/base-running] When a ball is hit in the air (i.e., a *fly ball*) and caught by the defending team, runners must return and touch the base they occupy—called *tagging up*—after the ball is first touched by a fielder.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Once they do this, they may attempt to advance at their own risk.
[src:outfielder/base-running] On a ball that touches the ground in fair territory, if there is a force, runners are required to run.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Base runners may attempt to advance at any time while the ball is alive, even before or while the pitcher is throwing a pitch.
[src:outfielder/base-running] The catcher—or pitcher, in lieu of delivering the pitch—often tries to prevent this by throwing the ball to one of the infielders in order to tag the runner.
[src:outfielder/base-running] This *pick-off attempt* is usually unsuccessful in tagging out the runner but is effective in keeping the runner closer to the base.
[src:outfielder/base-running] If the runner is tagged out while diving back to the base, it is called a *pickoff*.
[src:outfielder/base-running] If the runner attempts to advance to the next base but is tagged out before reaching it safely, he is *caught stealing*.
[src:outfielder/base-running] A successful attempt by the runner is called a *stolen base*.
[src:outfielder/base-running] If a pitch gets away from the catcher, runners may also try to advance.
[src:outfielder/base-running] This may be a *wild pitch*, if the pitcher is held responsible for the ball getting away, or a *passed ball* if the catcher is deemed to be at fault.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Sometimes the defending team will ignore a runner who is trying to steal a base; in this case a runner is not credited with a steal, and the base is attributed to *defensive indifference*.
[src:outfielder/base-running] An infielder who cleanly fields a ball hit on the ground, then throws it quickly and accurately, will usually get the ball to a base before the runner runs the 90 feet (27 m).
[src:outfielder/base-running] However, any hesitation or mistake on the part of the fielder may allow the runner to reach the base safely.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Teams scout the opposition and take advantage of players who are poor at defense.
[src:outfielder/base-running] For example, on a deep fly ball to center field with a man on second base, if the center fielder has a weak arm, the runner on second base may tag the base and attempt to reach third despite the risks of being tagged out.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Base running and hitting are coordinated to produce better results in the squeeze play and the hit and run play.
[src:outfielder/base-running] When the count is full and there are two outs, any runners forced to advance begin running as soon as the pitcher's motion obliges him to complete his pitch, as their distance from the base will not be the cause of any third out.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Good runners also try to get extra bases when a play is being made at a different base.
[src:outfielder/base-running] For example, a batter who hits a single should determine whether the defense's focus on another runner gives the batter a chance to reach second base.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Sliding into a base is an important part of base running.
[src:outfielder/base-running] The pop-up slide both ensures that the runner touches the base and elevates him to an upright posture to help him take additional bases if the defense misperforms.
[src:outfielder/base-running] A take-out slide tries to use a collision with a fielder to keep him from taking additional action, such as throwing to achieve a double play.
[src:outfielder/base-running] However, this move, when made independently of the attempt to reach the base, has been illegal since 2016 because of the potential for injury.
[src:outfielder/base-running] The base coach at third base, and any batter still at home plate, may watch the ball approaching the base and may signal the base runner on the optimum slide to avoid being tagged out.
[src:outfielder/base-running] The most baserunners allowed by a pitcher in a game since 1901 is 39, by Eddie Rommel, who pitched 17 innings in relief for the Philadelphia Athletics to defeat the Cleveland Indians, 18–17, on July 10, 1932.
[src:outfielder/base-running] The record number of baserunners in a season is 820, by John Coleman of the Philadelphia Quakers in 1883.
[src:outfielder/base-running] Wilbur Wood of the 1973 Chicago White Sox was the last pitcher to allow more than 500 baserunners in a season.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:outfielder/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] In the sport of baseball, each of the nine players on a team is assigned a particular **fielding position** when it is their turn to play defense.
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] Each position conventionally has an associated number, for use in scorekeeping by the official scorer: 1 (pitcher), 2 (catcher), 3 (first baseman), 4 (second baseman), 5 (third baseman), 6 (shortstop), 7 (left fielder), 8 (center fielder), and 9 (right fielder).
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] Collectively, these positions are usually grouped into three groups: the outfield (left field, center field, and right field), the infield (first base, second base, third base, and shortstop), and the battery (pitcher and catcher).
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] Fielders must be able to catch the ball well, as catching batted balls before they bounce is one way they can put the batter out, as well as create opportunities to prevent the advance of, and put out other runners.
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] Fielders often have to run, dive, and slide a great deal in the act of reaching, stopping, and retrieving a hit ball, and then setting themselves up to transfer the ball, all with the end goal of getting the ball as quickly as possible to another fielder.
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] They also run the risk of colliding with incoming runners during a tag attempt at a base.
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] Fielders may have different responsibilities depending on the game situation.
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] For example, when an outfielder is attempting to throw the ball from near the fence to one of the bases, an infielder may need to "cut off" the throw and then act as a relay thrower to help the ball cover its remaining distance to the target destination.
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] As a group, the outfielders are responsible for preventing home runs by reaching over the fence (and potentially doing a wall climb) for fly balls that are catchable.
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] The infielders are the ones who generally handle plays that involve tagging a base or runner, and also need quick reflexes in order to catch a batted ball before it leaves the infield.
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] The pitcher and catcher have special responsibilities to prevent base stealing, as they are the ones who handle the ball whenever it has not been hit.
[src:outfielder/baseball-positions] The catcher will also sometimes attempt to block the plate in order to prevent a run being scored.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:outfielder/baseball-reference-com] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] An **outfielder** is a person playing in one of the three defensive positions in baseball or softball, farthest from the batter.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] These defenders are the left fielder, the center fielder, and the right fielder.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] As an outfielder, their duty is to catch fly balls and ground balls then to return them to the infield for the out or before the runner advances, if there are any runners on the bases.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Outfielders normally play behind the six defensive players located in the infield: the pitcher, catcher, first baseman, second baseman, third baseman, and shortstop.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] The left fielder and right fielder are named based on their positions relative to the center fielder when looking out from home plate, with the left fielder positioned to the left of the center fielder and the right fielder positioned to the right.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] By convention, each of the nine defensive positions in baseball are numbered.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] The outfield positions are 7 (left fielder), 8 (center fielder) and 9 (right fielder).
[src:outfielder/outfielder] These numbers are shorthand designations useful in baseball scorekeeping and are not the same as the squad numbers worn on player uniforms.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Outfielders named to the MLB All-Century Team are Hank Aaron, Ty Cobb, Joe DiMaggio, Mickey Mantle, Willie Mays, Stan Musial, Pete Rose, Babe Ruth, Ted Williams, Carl Yastrzemski, and Ken Griffey Jr.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Players can be characterized as either corner outfielders or a center fielder.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Corner outfielders are often slower and have less defensive value than the center fielder.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] However, there are some important differences between right fielders and left fielders.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Right fielders tend to have the best throwing arms of the outfield so they can make the long throw to third base, but often are not as fast as left fielders.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Center fielders are generally the fastest and most athletic of the three, because they have to run the farthest in order to field balls in the gaps and back up the other outfielders when balls are hit to them.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Outfielders should also be able to read where the ball may be placed based on what the pitcher is throwing.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] They can tell what the pitcher is throwing by the middle infielders, second base and short stop, in which they show the numbers the catcher is giving to the pitcher behind their back to determine the pitch and tell where the ball could possibly be hit to.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Many of the best power hitters in baseball play in the outfield, where they do not have as constant involvement in fielding plays as other positions, especially before the institution of the designated hitter.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] For example, Babe Ruth was moved from pitcher to the outfield.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Left fielders and right fielders are more often slow power hitters, and center fielders are usually fast base-runners and good defensive players.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Center field is often considered the most difficult outfield position, requiring both a good throwing arm and speed.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Center fielders on many teams often bat lead off.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Players who do not routinely start games, but often substitute as a pinch hitter or defensive replacement in the outfield are referred to as fourth outfielders or even fifth outfielders.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] These players can usually play any of the three outfield positions.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Corner outfielders are outfielders who play the corner positions of right field and left field.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Corner outfielders often have less speed than center fielders, but make up for this deficiency with their offensive play.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Left fielders usually handle more chances because right-handed hitters tend to hit balls to the left, and right-handedness is more common in baseball, as in most things, than left-handedness.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Many left fielders have the speed to play center field, but lack the throwing ability required.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Right fielders typically have stronger arms, but are frequently (not always) slower and less agile defensively.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] Many corner outfielders are capable of playing in either right or left field.
[src:outfielder/outfielder] An example of an ultra-fast left fielder is Rickey Henderson (Ben Oglivie and Lou Brock can fit this description too), whereas the slow-footed but very strong-armed Carl Furillo, "The Reading Rifle", sets a standard for right fielders in the terms specified here.
